\[\begin{cases}\mathbf{S}_{0}=\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{1}}+\mathbf{I}_{ \alpha_{2}}+\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{3}}+\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{4}})=\mathbf{I}_{ \alpha_{1}}+\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{3}}=\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{2}}+\mathbf{I}_{\alpha _{4}}\\ \mathbf{S}_{1}=\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{3}}-\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{1}}\\ \mathbf{S}_{2}=\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{4}}-\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{2}}\end{cases}.\] (2)

Here, we can see \(\mathbf{S}_{0}\) describes the total intensity of the light, which is polarization-unrelated. In the following, we will use \(\mathbf{S}_{0,1,2}^{\text{L}}\) and \(\mathbf{S}_{0,1,2}^{\text{B}}\) to denote the Stokes parameters of \(\mathcal{L}\) and \(\mathcal{B}\) respectively.

The overall reconstruction process of our framework can be formulated as maximizing a posteriori of the output \(\mathcal{I}\) conditioned on the inputs \(\mathcal{L}\) and \(\mathcal{B}\) along with the fusing function \(f\) parameterized by \(\Psi\):

\[\operatorname*{argmax}_{\Psi}f(\mathcal{I}|\mathcal{L},\mathcal{B},\Psi).\] (3)To solve this maximum a posteriori estimation problem, we design a neural network-based three-phase fusing scheme to implement the fusing function \(f\), as shown in Fig. 2. First, the irradiance restoration phase restore the polarization-unrelated high-level irradiance information of the scene, by enhancing \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{L}}\) to obtain the coarse value of the total intensity of the light \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{t}}\) under the guidance of the color and structure cues provided by \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{B}}\) and \(\mathbf{S}_{1,2}^{\text{B}}\) respectively. Then, we compute \((\mathbf{x}^{\text{t}},\mathbf{y}^{\text{t}})\), which are the coarse values of the DoP and AoP in a Cartesian coordinate representation, and feed them into the polarization reconstruction phase to obtain the corresponding enhanced values \((\mathbf{x}^{\prime},\mathbf{y}^{\prime})\) with the help of \((\mathbf{x}^{\text{B}},\mathbf{y}^{\text{B}})\) (the DoP and AoP of \(\mathcal{B}\) in a Cartesian coordinate representation) along with the irradiance clues encoded in \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{t}}\), aiming to establish the physical correlation between the polarized images. Finally, we compute the coarse values of the polarized images \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\), and adopt an artifact suppression phase to obtain \(\mathbf{\Gamma}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\) that make up the clean and clear polarized snapshot \(\mathcal{I}\), by suppressing the artifacts in the image domain for increasing the quality of details.

### Phase1: Irradiance restoration

This phase aims to restore the polarization-unrelated high-level irradiance information for providing further guidance. As shown in Fig. 1, since \(\mathcal{L}\) would retain better contours than \(\mathcal{B}\), we propose to learn the residual between \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{L}}\) and \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{t}}\) instead of the residual between \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{B}}\) and \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{t}}\). However, \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{L}}\) usually suffers from color bias and noise, which would increase the difficulty of feature extraction, resulting in erroneous global tone and less salient local structure. Fortunately, despite that \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{B}}\) would suffer from motion blur, it still contains undamaged color information due to the relatively high SNR of \(\mathcal{B}\); besides, \(\mathbf{S}_{1,2}^{\text{L}}\) could provide distinctive structure information since both of them describe the difference between two polarized images (see Eq. (2)), which would highlight the regions with high gradients. Therefore, we propose to effectively explore the usage of \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{B}}\) and \(\mathbf{S}_{1,2}^{\text{L}}\).

Specifically, we first explicitly adopt two modal-specific feature encoders \(\mathcal{F}_{\text{enc}}^{\text{c}}\) and \(\mathcal{F}_{\text{enc}}^{\text{s}}\) to extract the multiscale color and structure features \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{s}}\) and \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{s}}\) from \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{B}}\) and \(\mathbf{S}_{1,2}^{\text{B}}\) respectively for guidance. Then, we propose to use three color and structure cue fusion (CSCF) modules to apply the guidance provided by \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{c}}\) and \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{s}}\) to \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{in}}\) in a successive manner, and output \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{out}}\) for restoring \(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{t}}\). Here, \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{in}}\) and \(\mathbf{F}_{1,2,3}^{\text{out}}\) denote the multiscale input and output features of the CSCF modules respectively, which are extracted from and fed into the encoder and decoder part of a modified autoencoder architecture [9] where a dense block [11] is inserted into the coarsest layer.

