**CSCF: color and structure cue fusion.** The CSCF module aims to address the issues of erroneous global tone and less salient local structure in the feature space. Without losing generality, we describe how the \(i\)-th scale (\(i=1,2,3\)) CSCF takes \(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{t}}\), \(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{s}}\), and \(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{in}}\) as the input and output \(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\text{out}}\), as shown in Fig. 3 (a). We first learn a multiplier \(\mathbf{m}_{i}\) and a bias \(\mathbf{b}_{i}\) from \(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{t}}\) by

\[\mathbf{m}_{i}=B_{c}(C_{m}(Sigmoid(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{c}})))\;\;\text{ and}\;\;\mathbf{b}_{i}=B_{c}(C_{b}(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{c}})),\] (4)

where \(B_{c}\) denotes a bottleneck block [8] used for feature projection, \(C_{m}\) and \(C_{b}\) denote two different convolution layers. Then, we apply an affine transformation to \(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\text{in}}\) using \(\mathbf{m}_{i}\) and \(\mathbf{b}_{i}\), to adjust the color in the feature space for solving the issue of erroneous global tone by

\[\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{t}}=\mathbf{m}_{i}\odot\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\text{in}}+ \mathbf{b}_{i},\] (5)

where \(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{t}}\) denote the transformed feature, \(\odot\) denotes element-wise product operation. Finally, to solve the issue of less salient local structure, we apply a deformable convolution layer [34]\(D\) to align the gradients and overcome the possible shifts caused by the exposure interval in the feature space by

\[\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\text{out}}=D(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{t}},\Delta\mathbf{P}_{i },\Delta\mathbf{M}_{i}),\] (6)

where \(\Delta\mathbf{P}_{i}\) and \(\Delta\mathbf{M}_{i}\) are the offsets of sampling points and the modulation scalars learned by

\[\Delta\mathbf{P}_{i}=B_{s}(C_{P}(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{s}}))\;\;\text{and} \;\;\Delta\mathbf{M}_{i}=B_{s}(C_{M}(\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\mathrm{s}})),\] (7)

where \(B_{s}\), \(C_{P}\), and \(C_{M}\) denotes another bottleneck block [8] and convolution layers respectively.

### Phase2: Polarization reconstruction

This phase aims to establish the physical correlation between the polarized images by reconstructing the high-quality DoP and AoP. To achieve it, previous methods usually choose to repair the degenerated values in the image domain [10; 25; 15; 33] or Stokes domain [32] for an indirect reconstruction, since the degeneration patterns of the DoP and AoP could be more complicated than the polarized images or Stokes parameters due to their non-linearity (see Eq. (1)), which could increase the ill-posedness. In contrast, we propose to reconstruct the DoP and AoP in a Cartesian coordinate representation, which can not only relieve the ill-posedness since the non-linearity reduces, but also optimize the values of the DoP and AoP in a direct manner to prevent error accumulation.

Here, we explain what is the Cartesian coordinate representation of the DoP and AoP: as shown in Fig. 4, if we regard \(\mathbf{p}\) and \(2\theta\) in Eq. (1) as the magnitude and angle of a vector \(\mathbf{\vec{S}}\) lying inside a unit circle, the Cartesian coordinate representation of \(\mathbf{\vec{S}}\) could be written as \((\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})\), which satisfying

\[\mathbf{x}=\frac{\mathbf{S}_{1}}{\mathbf{S}_{0}}\;\;\text{and}\;\;\mathbf{y}= \frac{\mathbf{S}_{2}}{\mathbf{S}_{0}}.\] (8)

