Specifically, we propose to learn the residual between \((\mathbf{x}^{\prime},\mathbf{y}^{\prime})\) and \((\mathbf{x}^{\prime},\mathbf{y}^{\prime})\), with the help of \((\mathbf{x}^{\text{B}},\mathbf{y}^{\text{B}})\) and \(\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{0}\), where

\[\mathbf{x}^{\text{t}}=\frac{\mathbf{S}^{\text{L}}_{1}}{\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{ 0}}\ \,\ \ \mathbf{y}^{\text{t}}=\frac{\mathbf{S}^{\text{L}}_{2}}{\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{ 0}}\ \,\ \ \mathbf{x}^{\text{B}}=\frac{\mathbf{S}^{\text{B}}_{1}}{\mathbf{S}^{\text{B}}_{ 0}}\ \ \text{and}\ \ \mathbf{y}^{\text{B}}=\frac{\mathbf{S}^{\text{B}}_{2}}{\mathbf{S}^{\text{B}}_{ 0}}.\] (9)

First, we propose to use a coherence-aware aggregation (CAG) module to estimate the coherence volumes \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}\) and \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{y}}\) from \(\mathbf{x}^{\text{B,t}}\), \(\mathbf{y}^{\text{B,t}}\), and \(\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{0}\). Then, we adopt two branches for reconstructing \(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\) and \(\mathbf{y}^{\prime}\) respectively. The first branch contains a feature encoder \(\mathcal{F}^{\text{x}}_{\text{enc}}\) and three cascaded coherence injection (CI) modules using \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}\) for guidance. Similarly, the second branch contains a feature encoder \(\mathcal{F}^{\text{y}}_{\text{enc}}\) and three cascaded CI modules using \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{y}}\) for guidance.

**CAG: coherence-aware aggregation.** The CAG module aims to aggregate the priors about the coherence between the polarization properties and the irradiance information. As shown in Fig. 3 (b), it contains two symmetrical parts for estimating \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}\) and \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{y}}\) respectively. Here, we only describe how to estimate \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}\) since the estimation process of \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{y}}\) could be similar. We first adopt two bottleneck blocks [8] to extract polarization features and irradiance features from \(\mathbf{x}^{\text{B,t}}\) and \(\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{0}\) respectively. Then, we project the extracted features into the coherence features \(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{x}}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times C\times H\times W}\) using a convolution layer, where \(N,C,H,W\) represent the batch size, number of channels, height, and width respectively. After that, inspired by CBAM [24] that can make full use of the inter-channel relationship of features, we propose to learn an attention vector \(\mathbf{A}_{\text{x}}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times C\times 1\times 1}\) to recalibrate \(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{x}}\) for obtaining \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times C\times H\times W}\):

\[\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}=\mathbf{A}_{\text{x}}\odot\mathbf{Z}_{\text{x}}=P(MLP( Sigmoid(\mathbf{Z}_{\text{x}})))\odot\mathbf{Z}_{\text{x}},\] (10)

where \(P\) denotes the global average pooling operation and \(MLP\) denotes a multi-layer perceptron.

**CI: coherence injection.** The CI module aims to inject the priors about coherence into the reconstruction of \(\mathbf{x}^{\text{t}}\) and \(\mathbf{y}^{\text{t}}\). To enlarge the receptive field and include long-range association, we choose to use Transformer modules [6] with cross-attention layers. Taking one of the CI module in the first branch (the branch for reconstructing \(\mathbf{x}^{\text{t}}\)) as an example, denoting its input as \(\mathbf{F}^{\text{in}}_{\text{x}}\) (from the previous CI module or \(\mathcal{F}^{\text{x}}_{\text{enc}}\)) and \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}\) (from the CAG module), we let \(\mathbf{F}^{\text{in}}_{\text{x}}\) to serve as the query vector and adopt convolution layers to learn the key vector and the value vector from both \(\mathbf{F}^{\text{in}}_{\text{x}}\) and \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{x}}\).

### Phase3: Artifact suppression

With \(\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{0}\) and \((\mathbf{x}^{\prime},\mathbf{y}^{\prime})\) available, we could compute the coarse values of the polarized images \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\). However, we should not output \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\) directly since their quality is still not satisfying. This is because \(\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{0}\) and \((\mathbf{x}^{\prime},\mathbf{y}^{\prime})\) are estimated from two different phases so that the irradiance-polarization consistency would break, bringing artifacts to the details. Therefore, we add an extra phase to refine \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\) for increasing the quality of details by suppressing the artifacts in the image domain.

Specifically, we propose to learn the residual between \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\) and \(\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\). According to Eq. (2), we choose to divide \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}\) into two groups (\(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,3}}\) and \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{2,4}}\)) first to ensure both of them contain the full irradiance information and each of them contains half of the polarization properties. Then, we use two convolution layers to extract the features of \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{1,3}}\) and \(\mathbf{I}^{\prime}_{\alpha_{2,4}}\) respectively, and adopt a feature merger \(\mathcal{F}_{\text{mer}}\) to obtain the merged dual-group features \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{mer}}\). After that, a U-Net backbone [18] is used to perform pixel-wise multi-scale feature refinement on \(\mathbf{F}_{\text{mer}}\), and another two convolution layers are adopted for decoding the refined dual-group features into the residuals of each group.

## 4 Implementation details

**Loss function.** The total loss function can be written as

\[L=L_{\text{s}}+L_{\text{p}}+L_{\text{r}},\] (11)

which consists of three terms to optimize the three phases respectively: irradiance loss \(L_{\text{s}}\), polarization loss \(L_{\text{p}}\), and refinement loss \(L_{\text{r}}\). The irradiance loss could be written as

\[L_{\text{s}}=\lambda_{\text{s}}^{\text{a}}L_{1}(\mathbf{S}^{\text{t}}_{0}, \mathbf{S}^{\text{gt}}_{0})+\lambda_{\text{s}}^{\text{b}}L_{\text{perc}}(\mathbf{S }^{\text{t}}_{0},\mathbf{S}^{\text{gt}}_{0}),\] (12)

where \(\lambda_{\text{s}}^{\text{ab}}\) are set to be 10.0 and 0.05 respectively, \(L_{1}\) and \(L_{\text{perc}}\) denote the \(\ell_{1}\) loss and perceptual loss respectively, the subscript gt labels the ground truth throughout this paper. The perceptual loss \(L_{\text{perc}}\) is defined as

\[L_{\text{perc}}(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{t}},\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{gt}})=L_{2}(\phi_ {h}(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{t}}),\phi_{h}(\mathbf{S}_{0}^{\text{gt}})),\] (13)

where \(L_{2}\) denotes the \(\ell_{2}\) loss, \(\phi_{h}\) denotes the feature map from \(h\)-th layer of VGG-19 network [20] pretrained on ImageNet [19], and we use activations from \(VGG_{3,3}\) convolution layer here. The polarization loss could be written as

\[L_{\text{p}}=\lambda_{\text{p}}^{\text{a}}(L_{1}(\mathbf{x}^{\prime},\mathbf{ x}^{\text{gt}})+L_{1}(\mathbf{y}^{\prime},\mathbf{y}^{\text{gt}}))+\lambda_{ \text{p}}^{\text{b}}(L_{\text{tv}}(\mathbf{x}^{\prime})+L_{\text{tv}}(\mathbf{ y}^{\prime}))+\lambda_{\text{p}}^{\text{c}}L_{\text{pol}}^{1}(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}, \mathbf{x}^{\text{gt}},\mathbf{y}^{\prime},\mathbf{y}^{\text{gt}}),\] (14)

where \(\lambda_{\text{p}}^{\text{a,b,c}}\) are set to be 1.0, 0.15, and 1.0 respectively, \(L_{\text{tv}}\) denotes the total variation loss, \(L_{\text{pol}}^{1}\) is a polarization-based regularization term to ensure the ratio between \(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\) and \(\mathbf{y}^{\prime}\) defined as

\[L_{\text{pol}}^{1}(\mathbf{x}^{\prime},\mathbf{x}^{\text{gt}},\mathbf{y}^{ \prime},\mathbf{y}^{\text{gt}})=L_{2}(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\odot\mathbf{y}^{ \text{gt}},\mathbf{y}^{\prime}\odot\mathbf{x}^{\text{gt}}).\] (15)

The refinement loss could be written as

\[L_{\text{r}}=\lambda_{\text{r}}^{\text{a}}L_{1}(\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}, \mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}^{\text{gt}})+\lambda_{\text{r}}^{\text{b}}L_{ \text{pol}}^{2}(\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}}),\] (16)

where \(\lambda_{\text{r}}^{\text{a,b}}\) are set to be 10.0 and 100.0 respectively, \(L_{\text{pol}}^{2}\) denotes another polarization-based regularization term defined as

\[L_{\text{pol}}^{2}(\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{1,2,3,4}})=L_{2}(\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{ 1}}+\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{3}},\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{2}}+\mathbf{I}_{\alpha_{4}}),\] (17)

which is similar to the one used in [30] for enforcing the preservation of polarization properties.

**Dataset preparation.** We propose to generate a synthetic dataset due to the fact that there is no public dataset for our settings. First, we choose the PLIE dataset [32] as our data source. It provides short-exposure polarized snapshots that suffer from low-light noise along with the corresponding high-quality reference snapshots captured by a Lucid Vision Phoenix polarization camera, which could serve as \(\mathcal{L}\) and \(\mathcal{I}\). Then, we adopt the approach proposed in [33] to generate the blurry polarized snapshots that suffer from motion blur, which could be served as \(\mathcal{B}\). To generate more severe motion blur for increasing the diversity, we add impulsive variation [1] to the motion trajectories. The images are resized and randomly cropped to \(256\times 256\) (\(512\times 512\)) pixels in the training (test) set. The training (test) set contains 7500 (300) different images in total.

**Training strategy.** Our framework is implemented using PyTorch with 2 NVIDIA 2080Ti GPUs, and a two-stage training strategy is applied. First, to ensure a stable initialization of the training process, we train the irradiance restoration phase and the polarization reconstruction phase independently for 300 epochs with learning rates of 0.01 and 0.0001 respectively. Then, we train the entire network for 100 epochs with learning rate of 0.0001, and in this training stage we multiply the loss terms \(L_{\text{s,p,r}}\) with 5.0, 10.0, and 10.0 respectively. For optimization, we use Adam optimizer [12] with \(\beta_{1}=0.5\), \(\beta_{2}=0.999\).

